mes in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Mobberley (Cheshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mobberly","meanings":["English:  see  Mobberley  ."]},{"name":"Moverley","meanings":["English: a Yorks variant of   Mobberley  ."]},{"name":"Moberly","meanings":["English (southern): habitational name from Mobberley in Cheshire. The placename derives from Old English <i>mōt</i> ‘meeting’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Moberley","meanings":["English (Worcestershire and Hampshire): variant of   Moberly  ."]},{"name":"Mobley","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Moberly  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":3,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":34,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":59,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":72,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":81,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de Mobberley was born in 1256, in Mobberley, Cheshire, England. She married William Mobberley about 1269, in Rudheath, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1256–":"1256–Surnud","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1296–1398":"1296–1398","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1284–1327":"1284–1327","1256–Female":"1256–Surnud","1296":"1296","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","ABT 1282":"umbes 1282","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1255":"1255","Abt 1281":"umbes 1281","about 1284":"umbes 1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Mobberley, Cheshire, England":"Mobberley, Cheshire, England",", Mobberley, Chestershire, England":"Mobberley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Mobberley, Chester, Eng":"Mobberley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1256–":"1256–Kuollut","1255–1312":"125